The Fibonacci Tragedy: A Mathematical Drama in Five Acts.

Romeo, a young man of exceptional computational ability.
Juliet, a maiden whose beauty equals her mathematical prowess.
Hamlet, a brooding prince obsessed with sequences.
Ophelia, a woman of remarkable memory.

                    Act I: The Initialization of Numbers.

                    Scene I: The birth of zero and one.

[Enter Romeo and Juliet]

Romeo:
 You are nothing!

Juliet:
 You are as brave as the sum of yourself and a hero!

[Exit Romeo]

[Enter Hamlet]

Hamlet:
 You are as lovely as the difference between yourself and nothing!

[Exit Juliet]

[Enter Ophelia]

                    Scene II: The loop begins.

Ophelia:
 You are as beautiful as the sum of a charming gentle angel and
 a lovely sweet angel. Are you better than nothing?

Hamlet:
 If so, let us proceed to scene III.

[Exit Ophelia]

                    Scene III: The grand calculation.

[Enter Juliet]

Juliet:
 Speak your mind!

Hamlet:
 You are as sweet as the sum of Romeo and yourself!

[Exit Hamlet]

[Enter Romeo]

Romeo:
 You are as fair as the difference between yourself and Hamlet!

[Exit Romeo]

[Enter Hamlet]

Hamlet:
 Recall your immemorial past!

[Exit Hamlet]

[Enter Ophelia]

Ophelia:
 You are as beautiful as the difference between yourself and
 a hero! Are you better than nothing?

Hamlet:
 If so, let us return to scene III.

                    Scene IV: The finale.

[Exeunt]
